Jaiz Bank Plc, Nigeria’s premier non-interest (Islamic) bank has recorded another impressive performance in the first half of this year amidst COVID-19 lockdown as it continued to improve its cost efficiency and risk management. The Bank’s half year results ended June 30, 2020 which was submitted to the Nigerian Stock Exchange (NSE) showed that profits for the period increased from N814.3m in half year 2019 to N1.171bn, signifying 43.87 percent increase. A statement from the bank said the Bank’s balance sheet size increased by 11.57 percent from N167.273bn as at December 31, 2019 to N186.625bn at the end of June 30, 2020. It said the Bank also grew its total income by 29.3 percent from N4.82bn as at June 2019 to N6.23bn at the end of June 2020, while earning per share rose by 174.48 percent from N1.45 in the first half of 2019 to N3.98 in the first half of 2020. Managing Director of the Bank, Mr. Hassan Usman, said the half year results further demonstrated that the Bank has the capacity to grow sustainably as large number of people are interested in it due to its ethical requirements. He assured that while maintaining steady focus on elements that contributed to improved performance thus far, he is hopeful that the Bank will end the year compared to the feat attained in 2019. Jaiz bank grows half-year profits by 295% JAIZ Bank posts N636.7m profit in Q1 Jaiz Bank pays shareholders N884m maiden dividend